I'm still addressing the comments and fixing the build. However, I tested this on Nertz and it does not seem to be working. No metrics are being emitted and I am not sure why. It only works if I invoke `jobMetrics.startMetricsReporting`, but not when I do `containerMetrics.startMetricsReporting`.

@liyinan926, @ibuenros do either of you see anything wrong with this implementation?

My understanding is that since `ContainerMetrics` is the parent of `JobMetrics` and, `JobMetrics` is the parent of `TaskMetrics`, that if I invoke `containerMetrics.startMetricsReporting` everything should be reported properly.

I also think we need an interface

interface ConfigStoreWithBatchFetches extends ConfigStore {
    Map<URI, Config> getOwnConfigs(Collection<URI> configUris, String version)
}

@liyinan926 and @ibuenros I found the issue.

It seems that in Typesafe's Config library the `.conf` files actually allow you to express the config in JSON format (according to the documentation on their Github page it actually uses a JSON superset called HOCON https://github.com/typesafehub/config#using-hocon-the-json-superset).

HOCON provides multiple ways of writing valid JSON (check the documentation link for examples). One such way is using the dot-notation. So a config such as `my.test.config=30` will actually be converted to

```
{
  "my" : {
    "test" : {
      "config" : "30"
    }
  }
}
```

The reason that this is problematic is that if you have the following two lines in your config file:

```
metrics.reporting.kafka.topic=MetricReport
metrics.reporting.kafka.topic.events=GobblinTrackingEvent
```

Then the resulting config is:

```
{
  "metrics": {
    "reporting": {
      "kafka": {
        "topic": {
          "events": "GobblinTrackingEvent"
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

My understanding is that you the first config sets a node in the JSON tree to `MetricReport`, but then the second config over-writes that node to `{"events" : "GobblinTrackingEvent"}`.

This is exactly the bug that I was hitting when testing this on Nertz. No metrics were being reported because the code could not find the name of the Kafka topic to report to. What happens is that `GobblinMetrics.startMetricsReporting` takes in a `Properties` object. So we have to use `YarnHelixUtils.configToProperties` to convert a `Config` object to a `Properties` object. The method uses `Config.entrySet` to get all the configs in the `Config` object. It seems as though `entrySet` will only return the leaf values of the JSON tree, so the resulting `Properties` object has nothing set for `metrics.reporting.kafka.topic`.

Is this behavior expected? Do we know of a way around this? This seems very different from how `gobblin.configuration.State` works, so it seems we could easily hit this issue with other config keys?

For now I can unblock this PR, because it seems the `gobblin-metrics` uses 3 config keys for reporting data to Kafka `metrics.reporting.kafka.topic.metrics`, `metrics.reporting.kafka.topic.events`, and `metrics.reporting.kafka.topic`. The last value is used as the default if either of the other two are not set. So we can still get things to work, but I still think we should discuss this on Monday.

The issue above has been discussed offline.

PR updated to address all comments. Confirmed this is working as expected after testing on Nertz.

